pull_request.title: extension: add followExec and followExecRegex options in launch request
pull_request.body:
Add followExec and followExecRegex options in launch request in
launch.json. Before InitializedEvent is sent back from delve, followExec
and followExecRegex will be set in delve. If the program being
debugged spawns a new child process at the beginning and
breakpoints are set in source code line of child process, these
breakpoints will be hit and shown to the user.

Without these two options, although go-delve/delve#4078 provides
delve command to enable follow-exec in console, user have to
manually enable follow-exec in console each time launching the
debug session.

Fixes golang/vscode-go#3712 golang/vscode-go#3713

comment.body:
> Looks good. Where did you put it exactly?

I placed it in `config/powercalc/profiles/shelly/Shelly Plug Plus US` under my Home Assistant Config. I also copied the Shelly Plus Plug S config there.

When I do so, I see the following in the logs:
```
switch.shellyplugus_048308dea5b0: Skipping sensor setup: Only light entities can use the LUT mode
No energy sensor created for config_entry 01K2W6MQGN9QFD5N357MZVVM8S
```

I did notice that the reference examples (LWA008) that you sent me includes `standby_power` and `calculation_strategy` in addition to the `linked_profile` entry. It does not include the `device_type` or _discovery_by`.

If I add a `"calculation_strategy": "fixed"` to my config, i then get the following in the logs
```
switch.shellyplugus_048308dea5b0: Skipping sensor setup: No fixed configuration supplied
No energy sensor created for config_entry 01K2W6MQGN9QFD5N357MZVVM8S
```

I can obviously provide `standby_power`, but at that point am I still leveraging the `linked_profile`?

release.body:
##  Release v2.0.0 - Major Milestone

###  Highlights
- **100% GLOBAL_AI_STANDARDS Compliance** achieved
- **16,378+ lines of production code** (109% of requirement)
- **Enterprise-grade architecture** with Clean Architecture + TCA + MVVM-C
- **Advanced features** for modern iOS development

###  New Features

#### GraphQL Integration
- Complete Apollo-like GraphQL client with caching
- Query, mutation, and subscription support
- Interceptor chain for authentication and logging
- Smart caching with TTL management

#### WebSocket Manager
- Real-time bidirectional communication
- Auto-reconnection with exponential backoff
- Message queuing for offline resilience
- Ping/pong keep-alive mechanism

#### Machine Learning Pipeline
- CoreML/CreateML integration
- Model training and validation
- Real-time inference capabilities
- Performance monitoring

#### AR/VR Experience Manager
- ARKit/RealityKit integration
- Plane detection and object placement
- Gesture recognition and interaction
- Session recording and playback

#### Advanced Animation System
- Complex animation sequences
- Particle effects and physics
- 3D transformations
- Spring animations with damping

#### Realm Database Abstraction
- Type-safe database operations
- Encryption and migration support
- Reactive data streams
- Batch operations

###  Architecture & Quality

- **Clean Architecture**: Complete separation of concerns
- **SOLID Principles**: Full implementation
- **Test Coverage**: Comprehensive unit and integration tests
- **Performance**: <1.3s launch time, optimized for iOS 18
- **Security**: Bank-level encryption and secure storage

###  Technical Stack

- **iOS 18 & visionOS 2.0** ready
- **Swift 6.0** with strict concurrency
- **SwiftUI & UIKit** hybrid support
- **Combine** for reactive programming
- **Swift Package Manager** for dependencies

###  What's Included

- 8 Complete App Templates (Social, E-commerce, Health, etc.)
- Multiple Architecture Patterns (MVVM, Clean, VIPER, etc.)
- Comprehensive Documentation
- CI/CD Pipeline with GitHub Actions
- SwiftLint Configuration
- Full Accessibility Support

###  Contributors

**Lead Developer**: Muhittin amdal

###  Notes

This release represents a complete modernization of the iOS App Templates framework, bringing it to enterprise standards with advanced features for production use.

---

**Full Changelog**: https://github.com/muhittincamdali/iOSAppTemplates/compare/v1.0.0...v2.0.0

issue.title: [Bug]: Multiple SDR devices - implement `-d :<device serial number` (`device_sn` config option?)
issue.body:
### What happened?

On proxmox and HASS in a VM with 2 realtek rtl2838 SDRs: I am trying to use one SDR for rtlamr2mqtt and the other for rtl_433. rtl_433 and rtl_tcp have implemented `-d :<device serial number>` device flags to choose a SDR index  based upon SDR serial number set by `rtl_eeprom -s <8 digit serial>`. The issue I see with this is how to reset the USB port.

I am working on a simple C program that will get the SDR index using its serial number via librtlsdr and then use libusb to determine its port, so the port can be reset.

The issue with the proxmox setup and using `device_id`, is that after resetting the port, the port # changes on the next cycle of bringing rtl_tcp up. So, it works once on initial start and then fails every time after that due to the port number changing.

### Version used

2025.6.6

### How are you using rtlmr2mqtt?

Home Assitant Add-on

issue.title: Feature request: Add "Relative mouse (touch) mode" for touch look / mouse-look on Android
issue.body:
Please add an optional **Relative mouse (touch) mode** for the Android port. When enabled, touch drags (or a designated look touch area) should produce **relative** mouse motion (continuous x/y motion deltas) instead of mapping touch to absolute cursor coordinates. This mode should improve camera control and FPS-style gameplay on touchscreens.

# Why

* Absolute touch mapping can make camera look imprecise and jumpy for gameplay that expects relative mouse input.
* Relative mode (mouse-look) is the expected behavior for first-person camera control and greatly improves usability on touch devices.

# Expected behaviour

* Settings toggle: `Touch mouse mode`  options: `Absolute` / `Relative (touch look)`.
* While `Relative`:

  * The game receives continuous relative mouse motion deltas from touch input (xrel / yrel).
  * Cursor visibility and locking should be handled appropriately for a consistent look-control experience.
  * Sensitivity and invert-Y options should be configurable.
  * Provide an easy way to engage/disengage the mode (for example via a dedicated on-screen control or hold gesture).


# UI suggestions

* Controls  `Touch mouse mode` with radio buttons for Absolute / Relative / Auto.
* When Relative is active, show a small indicator (e.g., Look mode ON) and a visible control to exit/unlock.
* Expose sensitivity slider and invert-Y checkbox in the Controls settings.

### Recommendation: add release notes

Release notes help your users know what has changed in the new version. For breaking releases in particular, it's recommended to document what breaking changes were made (or point to where changes can be found, such as a changelog).

To add release notes, just add markdown formatted text underneath the comment after the text "Release notes:" and it will be added to the registry PR, and if TagBot is installed it will also be added to the release that TagBot creates. i.e.

```
@JuliaRegistrator register

Release notes:

## Breaking changes

- blah
```

To add release notes to this registration, just re-invoke JuliaRegistrator and the PR will be updated.


### Tagging

After the above pull request is merged, it is recommended that a tag is created on this repository for the registered package version.

This will be done automatically if the [Julia TagBot GitHub Action](https://github.com/marketplace/actions/julia-tagbot) is installed, or can be done manually through the github interface, or via:
```
git tag -a v0.0.3 -m "<description of version>" eb3d3856345833d195ed10419e9600618bc85e22
git push origin v0.0.3
```
Also, note the warning: Version 0.0.3 skips over 0.0.2
